## 5. Configure NFS Share

The Debian VM must access the dataset via NFS.

In TrueNAS:

```
Sharing → Unix Shares (NFS) → Add
```

Configuration:

```
Path:                /mnt/tank/backups/app-exports
Authorized Networks: 192.168.178.141/32
```

> **Note:** The authorized network is set to a single host using `/32` CIDR notation. If your VM's IP changes, the NFS mount will fail. To prevent this, either set a DHCP reservation on your router for the VM, or use a subnet (`192.168.178.0/24`) to allow all hosts on the network.

> **Permissions:** If the script user on the Debian VM (typically `root`) does not match the dataset owner on TrueNAS, you will get `Permission Denied` errors. In TrueNAS, edit the NFS share and set **Mapall User** to `root`. This maps all incoming NFS requests to that user, preventing permission mismatches.

---

## 6. Mount the Dataset on Debian VM

Edit the filesystem table:

```bash
sudo nano /etc/fstab
```

Add:

```
192.168.178.139:/mnt/tank/backups/app-exports  /mnt/truenas-app-backups  nfs  rw,hard,timeo=600,retrans=5,nofail  0 0
```

| Option | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `rw` | read/write access |
| `hard` | retries forever instead of failing writes — prevents silent data corruption |
| `timeo=600` | timeout in tenths of seconds (60 seconds) |
| `retrans=5` | retry count before returning an error |
| `nofail` | system still boots if mount fails |

> **Why `hard` instead of `soft`:** A `soft` mount returns an error to the writing process if the NFS server becomes temporarily unreachable. For backup workloads, this can cause silent data corruption — the script may continue believing the write succeeded. A `hard` mount retries indefinitely until the server responds. Combined with `nofail`, the system still boots cleanly if TrueNAS is offline at startup.

Create mount directory:

```bash
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/truenas-app-backups
```

Mount the share:

```bash
sudo mount -a
```

Verify mount:

```bash
ls /mnt/truenas-app-backups
```

Expected output:

```
immich
paperless
```

