## 11. Paperless Backup Script

Create script:

```bash
sudo nano /usr/local/bin/backup-paperless.sh
```

Script:

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash

set -euo pipefail

DATE=$(date +%F)

# TrueNAS destination
DEST="/mnt/truenas-app-backups/paperless"

# Temporary location inside container
TMP="/tmp/paperless-export"

mkdir -p "$DEST"

# Verify the TrueNAS mount is available before proceeding.
# Without this check, a failed mount would cause the export to write to the
# local filesystem instead of TrueNAS, silently defeating the backup design.
if ! mountpoint -q /mnt/truenas-app-backups; then
    echo "ERROR: TrueNAS backup mount not available"
    exit 1
fi

# Verify the mount is actually writable, not just present.
# A stale NFS mount can pass the mountpoint check but fail on writes.
if ! touch /mnt/truenas-app-backups/.mount_test 2>/dev/null; then
    echo "ERROR: Backup destination not writable — mount may be stale"
    exit 1
fi
rm -f /mnt/truenas-app-backups/.mount_test

# Check available disk space on the backup destination.
# Exports can grow large over time — a full dataset causes cryptic failures mid-export.
# Requires at least 1GB free before proceeding.
FREE=$(df -P /mnt/truenas-app-backups | awk 'NR==2 {print $4}')
if [ "$FREE" -lt 1048576 ]; then
    echo "ERROR: Less than 1GB free space on backup destination (${FREE}KB available)"
    exit 1
fi

echo "Starting Paperless export $(date)"

cleanup() {
    # Attempt to remove temporary export directory
    docker exec paperless-webserver-1 rm -rf "$TMP" 2>/dev/null || \
        echo "Warning: cleanup of $TMP failed" >&2

    # Remove temporary archive
    docker exec paperless-webserver-1 rm -f /tmp/paperless-${DATE}.tar.gz 2>/dev/null || \
        echo "Warning: cleanup of archive failed" >&2
}

# Runs on both success and failure to prevent container disk buildup
trap cleanup EXIT

# Verify the Paperless container is running before attempting export.
docker ps --format '{{.Names}}' | grep -q paperless-webserver-1 \
    || { echo "ERROR: Paperless container not running"; exit 1; }

# NOTE:
# $TMP expands on the host and becomes /tmp/paperless-export inside the container.
# This is intentional because /tmp exists inside the container filesystem.
echo "Running Paperless document exporter..."
docker exec paperless-webserver-1 \
    python manage.py document_exporter "$TMP"

# Compress export directory inside container.
# Uses pigz (parallel gzip) if available for faster compression on multi-core CPUs,
# falls back to standard gzip otherwise.
docker exec paperless-webserver-1 bash -c \
    "command -v pigz >/dev/null 2>&1 \
        && tar -I pigz -cf /tmp/paperless-${DATE}.tar.gz -C \"${TMP}\" . \
        || tar -czf /tmp/paperless-${DATE}.tar.gz -C \"${TMP}\" ."

# Copy archive to TrueNAS dataset
docker cp paperless-webserver-1:/tmp/paperless-${DATE}.tar.gz \
    "$DEST/paperless-${DATE}.tar.gz"

echo "Paperless backup completed $(date)"
```

Make executable:

```bash
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/backup-paperless.sh
```

| Step | Purpose |
|---|---|
| mount guard | exits if TrueNAS NFS mount is unavailable — prevents export writing to local disk |
| write test | verifies the mount is actually writable — catches stale NFS mounts that pass the mountpoint check |
| disk space guard | exits if less than 1GB free on destination — prevents cryptic mid-export failures |
| container guard | exits cleanly with a clear error if the container isn't running |
| `document_exporter` | exports documents to a directory |
| `tar` inside container | creates compressed archive — uses `pigz` for parallel compression if installed, falls back to `gzip` |
| `docker cp` | copies archive to TrueNAS |
| `trap cleanup EXIT` | always cleans up container temp files on both success and failure |

> **Note on variable expansion:** `$TMP` and `$DATE` are host shell variables. They expand on the host before being passed to the container. The container receives fully resolved paths such as `/tmp/paperless-export` and `/tmp/paperless-2026-03-06.tar.gz`.

> **Note on container name:** `paperless-webserver-1` is the default container name when using Docker Compose from the `paperless-ngx` directory. If you deploy from a differently named directory or use a custom stack name, the container name will differ. Verify with `docker ps | grep paperless` before running the script.

