## 12. Immich Backup Script

Before writing the script, find your actual Immich container names:

```bash
docker ps | grep immich
```

Common names you may see:

```
immich_server
immich-server
immich_server_1
immich_server_immich-server_1
```

Once you have confirmed the correct server and postgres container names, update them in the script and in all restore commands. Then inspect the upload volume path:

```bash
docker inspect <your-immich-server-container> --format '{{ json .Mounts }}'
```

Look for the mount with `Destination: /usr/src/app/upload` and note the `Source` path on the host. Update `IMMICH_UPLOAD` in the script accordingly.

Create script:

```bash
sudo nano /usr/local/bin/backup-immich.sh
```

Script:

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash

set -euo pipefail

DATE=$(date +%F)

# CHANGE THIS to the actual path discovered from docker inspect
IMMICH_UPLOAD="/mnt/immich/library"

DEST="/mnt/truenas-app-backups/immich"

mkdir -p "$DEST"

echo "Starting Immich database dump $(date)"

# Verify the TrueNAS backup mount is available before proceeding.
# If the NFS mount has silently failed and the directory appears empty,
# rsync --delete-delay would delete all files in the destination.
if ! mountpoint -q /mnt/truenas-app-backups; then
    echo "ERROR: TrueNAS backup mount not available at /mnt/truenas-app-backups"
    exit 1
fi

# Verify the mount is actually writable, not just present.
if ! touch /mnt/truenas-app-backups/.mount_test 2>/dev/null; then
    echo "ERROR: Backup destination not writable — mount may be stale"
    exit 1
fi
rm -f /mnt/truenas-app-backups/.mount_test

# Dump the Immich database only (not all system databases).
# pg_dump targets the single 'immich' database — smaller, faster, and avoids
# unnecessary system roles and objects that pg_dumpall would include.
docker exec immich_postgres \
    pg_dump -U postgres immich > "$DEST/immich-db-dump-${DATE}.sql"

echo "Starting Immich library rsync $(date)"

# Verify the Immich upload directory exists before running rsync.
# If the path has changed or the volume is unmounted, rsync against a missing
# source with --delete-delay would remove all files from the destination.
if [ ! -d "$IMMICH_UPLOAD" ]; then
    echo "ERROR: Immich upload directory not found at $IMMICH_UPLOAD"
    exit 1
fi

rsync -av --numeric-ids --delete-delay --info=progress2 \
    "$IMMICH_UPLOAD/" \
    "$DEST/library/"

echo "Immich backup completed $(date)"
```

Make executable:

```bash
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/backup-immich.sh
```

| Step | Purpose |
|---|---|
| mount guard | exits cleanly if the NFS mount is unavailable — prevents rsync from deleting the destination if the source appears empty |
| write test | verifies the mount is actually writable — catches stale NFS mounts that pass the mountpoint check |
| source directory guard | exits if `IMMICH_UPLOAD` path does not exist — prevents accidental empty-source deletion |
| `pg_dump immich` | dumps only the Immich database — smaller, faster, no unnecessary system objects |
| `rsync -a` | archive mode — preserves permissions, timestamps, symlinks |
| `rsync --numeric-ids` | preserves UID/GID numerically — prevents permission drift if user IDs differ between systems |
| `rsync --delete-delay` | defers deletions until after transfer, preventing catastrophic loss if source disappears |
| `rsync --info=progress2` | shows overall transfer progress during manual runs — cron logs remain clean |
| separate `library/` subdir | keeps DB dump and image files clearly separated on TrueNAS |

> **Note on `--info=progress2`:** unlike the default per-file output, this flag shows a single updating line with overall progress and speed. In cron, it produces one summary line per transfer rather than flooding the log with per-file entries.

> **Important:** Immich stores all metadata — albums, people tags, sharing, organisational structure — in its PostgreSQL database, not in the image files themselves. Backing up only the library files would leave you with images but no metadata on restore. Always run the database dump before rsync.

