## 13. rclone Upload Script

Create script:

```bash
sudo nano /usr/local/bin/pcloud-export-backup.sh
```

Script:

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash

# set -e is intentionally omitted:
# rclone may return non-zero on partial failures (locked files, transient
# network issues). We handle errors manually via $STATUS instead.
set -uo pipefail

SOURCE="/mnt/truenas-app-backups"
REMOTE="pcloud:homelab-app-exports"

# Dated backup-dir acts as a remote recycle bin.
# If files are deleted from TrueNAS by accident or a script bug,
# rclone moves them here instead of permanently deleting them from pCloud.
BACKUP_DIR="pcloud:homelab-app-exports-deleted/$(date +%F)"

LOG="/var/log/pcloud-export-backup.log"

echo "========== pCloud upload started $(date) ==========" >> "$LOG"

# Verify the TrueNAS mount is available before syncing.
# If the mount has silently failed and the directory appears empty,
# rclone sync would propagate the deletions to pCloud.
if ! mountpoint -q /mnt/truenas-app-backups; then
    echo "ERROR: TrueNAS mount not available — aborting upload" >> "$LOG"
    echo "Upload aborted $(date)" >> "$LOG"
    exit 1
fi

# Verify the mount is actually writable, not just present.
if ! touch /mnt/truenas-app-backups/.mount_test 2>/dev/null; then
    echo "ERROR: TrueNAS mount not writable — possible stale NFS mount" >> "$LOG"
    echo "Upload aborted $(date)" >> "$LOG"
    exit 1
fi
rm -f /mnt/truenas-app-backups/.mount_test

mkdir -p /var/tmp/rclone-partial

rclone sync "$SOURCE" "$REMOTE" \
    --backup-dir "$BACKUP_DIR" \
    --transfers 4 \
    --checkers 8 \
    --retries 5 \
    --low-level-retries 10 \
    --ignore-errors \
    --partial \
    --partial-dir /var/tmp/rclone-partial \
    --human-readable \
    --log-file "$LOG" \
    --log-level INFO

STATUS=$?

if [ $STATUS -ne 0 ]; then
    echo "rclone finished with warnings (exit code $STATUS)" >> "$LOG"
else
    echo "========== Upload completed successfully $(date) ==========" >> "$LOG"
fi
```

Make executable:

```bash
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/pcloud-export-backup.sh
```

| Flag | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `sync` | ensures destination mirrors source |
| `--backup-dir` | moves deleted/overwritten files to a dated folder instead of permanently deleting them |
| `--transfers` | parallel upload count |
| `--checkers` | verification threads |
| `--retries` | retry attempts per file |
| `--ignore-errors` | prevents abort on single file failure |
| `--partial` | keeps partially uploaded files on interruption |
| `--partial-dir` | stages incomplete uploads in `/var/tmp/rclone-partial` — persistent across reboots, keeps incomplete files off the TrueNAS dataset, prevents snapshot pollution |
| `--human-readable` | log sizes as `2.4 GiB` instead of raw byte counts |
| `--log-level INFO` | useful diagnostics without excessive verbosity |

> **Why `--backup-dir` instead of plain `sync`:** `rclone sync` without a backup directory will permanently delete files from pCloud if they are removed from TrueNAS — whether intentionally or due to a script bug. `--backup-dir` moves those files into a dated folder (`homelab-app-exports-deleted/YYYY-MM-DD`) on pCloud instead, giving you a recoverable history. You can periodically clean up old dated folders manually.

