## 15. Daily Integrity Check Script

Running `rclone check` daily verifies that the pCloud copy exactly matches the TrueNAS dataset. This catches silent corruption or incomplete uploads within 24 hours — long before you ever need a restore. A weekly schedule would leave up to 6 days of undetected inconsistency given that backups run daily.

Create script:

```bash
sudo nano /usr/local/bin/pcloud-integrity-check.sh
```

Script:

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash

set -uo pipefail

SOURCE="/mnt/truenas-app-backups"
REMOTE="pcloud:homelab-app-exports"

LOG="/var/log/pcloud-integrity-check.log"

echo "========== Integrity check started $(date) ==========" >> "$LOG"

# Verify the TrueNAS mount is available before checking.
# A failed mount would cause rclone to see an empty source and
# incorrectly report every file on pCloud as missing.
if ! mountpoint -q /mnt/truenas-app-backups; then
    echo "ERROR: TrueNAS mount not available — integrity check skipped $(date)" >> "$LOG"
    exit 1
fi

rclone check "$SOURCE" "$REMOTE" \
    --one-way \
    --human-readable \
    --log-file "$LOG" \
    --log-level INFO

STATUS=$?

if [ $STATUS -ne 0 ]; then
    echo "========== Integrity check FAILED $(date) (exit code $STATUS) ==========" >> "$LOG"
    echo "Review $LOG immediately and consider re-running the upload script." >> "$LOG"
else
    echo "========== Integrity check passed — pCloud matches TrueNAS $(date) ==========" >> "$LOG"
fi
```

Make executable:

```bash
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/pcloud-integrity-check.sh
```

| Flag | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `check` | compares file size and modification time — does not transfer any data |
| `--one-way` | verifies all TrueNAS files exist and match in pCloud, ignoring extra files on pCloud — correct since pCloud may contain historical files from `--backup-dir` |
| `--human-readable` | sizes shown as `2.4 GiB` rather than raw byte counts |
| `--log-level INFO` | records every file checked, not just errors |

> **What `rclone check` detects:** files present on TrueNAS but missing from pCloud (incomplete uploads), files present on pCloud but missing from TrueNAS (unexpected deletions), and size or modification time mismatches. By default `rclone check` compares file size and modification time rather than full cryptographic checksums — this is fast and sufficient for most homelab use. Add `--download` for byte-level verification, but this forces a full download of every file and will be significantly slower.

> **What to do on failure:** a non-zero exit means at least one file differs. Review the log to identify which files are affected, then re-run `/usr/local/bin/pcloud-export-backup.sh` to resync. If corruption is on the TrueNAS side, restore from a ZFS snapshot before resyncing.

